ss1.p:
The basis for this term is the electrostatic repulsion between protons. To a very rough approximation, the nucleus can be considered a sphere of uniform charge density. The potential energy of such a charge distribution can be shown to be
\frac{3}{5} \frac{1}{4 \pi \epsilon_{0}} \frac{Q^{2}}{R}
where Q is the total charge and R is the radius of the sphere. Identifying Q with Z e, and noting as above that the radius is proportional to A^{1/3}, we get close to the form of the Coulomb term. However, because electrostatic repulsion will only exist for more than one proton, Z^2 becomes Z(Z-1).

The value of a_{C} can be approximately calculated using the equation above. In natural units this is
\frac{3}{5} \frac{\alpha}{R_0}
where \alpha is the fine structure constant and A^{1/3}R_0 is the radius of a nucleus, giving R_0 to be approximately 1.5 femtometers. This gives a_C an approximate theoretical value of 0.58 MeV, not far from the measured value.

\delta(A,Z) = \begin{cases} +\delta_{0} & Z,N \mbox{ even } (A \mbox{ even}) \\ 0 & A \mbox{ odd} \\ -\delta_{0} & Z,N \mbox{ odd } (A \mbox{ even})\end{cases}

where


\delta_{0} = \frac{a_{P}}{A^{1/3}}


Due to 


Pauli exclusion principle

 the nucleus would have a lower energy if the number of protons with spin up will be equal to the number of protons with spin down. This is also true for neutrons. Only if both Z and N are even, both protons and neutrons can have equal numbers of spin up and spin down particles. This is a similar effect to the asymmetry term.

The factor A^{-1/3} is not easily explained theoretically. The Fermi ball calculation we have used above, based on the liquid drop model but neglecting interactions, will give an A^{-1} dependence, as in the asymmetry term. This means that the actual effect for large nuclei will be larger than expected by that model. This should be explained by the interactions between nucleons; For example, in the shell model, two protons with the same quantum numbers (other than
spin
) will have completely overlapping wavefunctions and will thus have greater strong interaction between them and stronger binding energy. This makes it energetically favourable (i.e. having lower energy) for protons to pair in pairs of opposite spin. The same is true for neutrons.

sec.p:
By maximizing B(A,Z) with respect to Z, we find the number of protons Z of the stable nucleus of atomic weight A. We get
Z = {1\over 2} A {1\over 1 + A^{2/3} {a_C\over 4 a_A}}
This is roughly A/2 for light nuclei, but for heavy nuclei there is an even better agreement with nature.
